sentences.content: The reading companion is a web application (app) originally developed for the primary user .

It presents multimodal content to be read aloud and highlights the current word to be recited and corrects mispronunciations without a human companion through a browser that supports ReactJS and Speech Recognition Web API.

To balance the therapeutic challenge with ongoing self doubt and subsequent frustration, the user is afforded a (configurable) number of retries before the app recites the "stuck" word and advances to the next word.
The app also can recites
As Ronlyn worked with her Speech Language Pathologists, additional features have been incorporated based on their recommendations to support word finding and sentence completion.
The primary user lost much of her fluency to aphasia.
Even though she lost verbal skills, she is still able to read, albeit slowly and somewhat arduously.
Oral reading of familiar content that containing visual and verbal (written and oral) cues allows her to practice expressing herself with better execution.
The model user is much less apt to question the accuracy of the corrective feedback from an app than a person, especially a person whose primary role is advocative rather than therpeutic.
What are the key reading companion features

First and foremost, the reading companion reads along with the user by listening while the user reads aloud, recognizes and advances the current word to be spoken to the next word, waits for the correct word to be spoken and eventually states the word after prescribed retry counts or listening duration is exceeded.
The companion can also synthesize the text to the user in different ways by reciting the:
current word
current word and advancing to the next word
current sentence upto the current word
entire sentence
entire section.
In any of these modes, the current word can either stay unchanged or advanced to the next unrecited word.
